{{Italic title}} The '''''Historia Scholastica''''' is a twelfth-century [[Biblical paraphrase]] written in [[Medieval Latin]] by [[Petrus Comestor]].<ref name="Morney1993">{{cite journal |authorlink=James H. Morey |first=James H. |last=Morey |title=Peter Comestor, Biblical Paraphrase, and the Medieval Popular Bible |journal=Speculum |volume=68 |issue=1 |date=January 1993 |pages=6–35 |doi=10.2307/2863832}}</ref> Sometimes called the "Medieval Popular Bible", it draws on the Bible and other sources, including the works of classical scholars and the [[Fathers of the Church]], to present a [[universal history]] (universal, that is, from the perspective of [[medieval Europe]]).<ref name="Morney1993"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Jones|first1=Gareth|last2=Arrandale|first2=Rick|title=Blackwell Companion to Modern Theology|year=2007|publisher=Blackwell|isbn=1-4051-5975-8|page=136}}</ref>
The ''Historia Scholastica'' was a required part of the [[core curriculum]] at the [[University of Paris]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and other universities, and a significant [[secondary source]] of popular biblical knowledge from its completion around 1173<ref>{{cite book|last=Ma'oz|first=Moshe|title=The Meeting of Civilizations: Muslim, Christian, and Jewish|year=2009|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=1-84519-395-4|pages=48–50}}</ref> through the fifteenth century, although after about 1350 it was gradually supplanted by newer works.<ref name="Morney1993"/><ref name="Seybolt">{{cite journal|last=Seybolt|first=Robert Francis|title=The ''Legenda Aurea'', Bible, and ''Historia Scholastica''|journal=Speculum|date=Jul 1946|volume=21|issue=3|pages=339–342|doi=10.2307/2851378}}</ref> It was translated into every major Western European [[vernacular]] of the period.<ref name="Morney1993"/> Numerous paraphrases and abridgements were produced, in [[Latin]] and vernacular languages.<ref name="Morney1993"/>
It was among the [[incunabula|earliest printed works]], with editions appearing c. 1470 in both [[Strasbourg]] and [[Reutlingen]].<ref name="Morney1993"/>
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== {{Wikisourcelang|la|Historia Scholastica|Historia Scholastica (1543 Lyons edition)}}
