'''Overclass''' is a recent and [[pejorative]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=znDscu7MVcEC&pg=PT222&dq=overclass&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IxAoT-byKYOFtgeCvczxBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=overclass&f=false The next American nation: the new nationalism and the fourth American revolution - Michael Lind - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FYMrsb2u_lIC&pg=PA153&dq=overclass&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IxAoT-byKYOFtgeCvczxBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=overclass&f=false Fighting Poverty, Inequality and Injustice: A Manifesto Inspired by Peter ... - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> term for the most powerful group in a social [[hierarchy]]. Users of the term generally imply excessive and [[unjust]] [[Privilege (social inequality)|privilege]] and exploitation of the rest of society.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3QAQAQAAMAAJ&q=overclass&dq=overclass&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IxAoT-byKYOFtgeCvczxBA&redir_esc=y Chronicles - Rockford Institute - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cPPmmpNhb4IC&pg=PA23&dq=overclass&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IxAoT-byKYOFtgeCvczxBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=overclass&f=false This Land Is Their Land: Reports from a Divided Nation - Barbara Ehrenreich - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dM_yXS9leCEC&dq=overclass&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TxEoT9zRCujo2gW7q6zcAg&redir_esc=y Delight of the Overclass! Demise of the Middleclass! - Jay T. Baldwin - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
Perhaps the most commonly agreed-upon "overclass" consists of leaders in [[international business]], [[International finance|finance]] and the [[war industry]].<ref>{{cite book |author = [[David Rothkopf|Rothkopf, David J.]] | title = Superclass: the global power elite and the world they are making | publisher = [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] | year = 2008 | isbn = 0-374-27210-7}}</ref>
The influence of the actions by the overclass have been rigorously studied, particularly with regards to notions of intersections between the overclass and specific races. Most notable of these racial overclasses is the [[NEWBO]], or NEW Black Overclass in America.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29413966/ns/business-cnbc_tv/t/cnbc-special-report-new-black-overclass/ |title=CNBC Special Report: The New Black Overclass |last1=Hawkins |first1=Lee |date=February 26, 2009 |website=nbcnews.com |publisher=[[NBCNews.com]] |access-date=September 7, 2016 |quote=}}</ref>
The word is fairly recent: the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' included it only in December 2004.<ref>[http://www.oed.com/help/updates/ou-overzealousness.html Quarterly updates to OED Online]</ref> But it has been in use since at least 1995. Some writers compare it to the more familiar ''[[underclass]]'':
{{quote|We now have a quite new phenomenon in the history of the republic: two radically isolated sectors of the population, the underclass and the overclass. Both are in an adversarial posture toward the great majority of Americans, the overclass by virtue of ambition and unbounded self-esteem, the underclass by virtue of social incompetence and [[anomie]]. Between the two there is a fearful symmetry on many scores, but their service to each other is far from equal.<ref>[http://www.leaderu.com/ftissues/ft9608/public.html Farewell to the Overclass] 1996 [[Richard John Neuhaus]]</ref>}}
