{{Infobox organization |name = USAction |image = USAction_logo.jpeg |size = |membership = |caption = |formation = 1999 |website = {{url|http://www.usaction.org}} |affiliations = |leader_title = Executive Director |leader_name = Fred Azcarate |merged = [[People's Action]] }}
'''USAction''' was a [[501(c) organization#501(c)(4)|501(c)(4)]] federation of [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] community organizing groups.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jamieson|first1=Dave|title=Fred Azcarate Leaves AFL-CIO To Head Community Organizing Network USAction|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/16/fred-azcarate-afl-cio-us-action_n_3282811.html|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=Huffington Post|date=May 16, 2013}}</ref> It was founded in 1999. Its [[501(c) organization#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] counterpart was the '''USAction Education Fund'''.
In September 2007, '''[[TrueMajority]]''' and its related organization '''TrueMajorityACTION''' merged with USAction.<ref>USAction website, "History and Achievements," {{cite web |url=http://usaction.org/about-us/history-achievements/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-07-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630182438/http://usaction.org/about-us/history-achievements/ |archivedate=2017-06-30 |df= }} </ref>
==Activities== In 2008, USAction joined [[Health Care for America Now]], a coalition of labor unions and liberal advocacy groups pushing for affordable health care and stricter regulation of the health insurance industry. USAction committed at least $500,000 to the group's efforts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Evans|first1=Will|title=Profile: Health Care for America Now|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94482532|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=NPR|date=September 10, 2008}}</ref>
In 2009, USAction launched a campaign to "Dog the Blue Dogs." The [[Blue Dog Coalition]] is a caucus of United States Congressional Representatives from the Democratic Party who identify themselves as moderates and conservatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Ben|title='Common Purpose'|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/bensmith/0409/Common_Purpose.html|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=Politico|date=April 8, 2009}}</ref>
In 2012, USAction was part of a coalition of liberal advocacy groups that announced that companies making direct corporate contributions to influence elections would face consumer boycotts, campaigns to divest pension fund money, stockholder lawsuits, actions at stockholder meetings and widespread social media exposure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Froomkin|first1=Dan|title=Secret Campaign Spending Under Attack By Reform Groups|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/12/campaign-spending-secret-donations-ceos_n_1339491.html|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=Huffington Post|date=March 12, 2012}}</ref>
